HEADWORD: Magistrate
<hw>Mag"is*trate</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>magistratus</ets>, fr. <ets>magister</ets> master: cf. F.
<ets>magistrat</ets>. See <er>Master</er>.]</ety> <def>A person clothed
with power as a public civil officer; a public civil officer invested
with the executive government, or some branch of it.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧All
Christian rulers and <xex>magistrates</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Book of Com.
Prayer.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Of <qex>magistrates</qex> some also are supreme, in whom the
sovereign power of the state resides; others are subordinate.</q>
<rj><qau>Blackstone.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

